        <body>       
                 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>1 Thornby Place<lb/>
                Maina &#91;&#63;&#93;ale<lb/>
                8 July 1887&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Having through the medium<lb/> of The American Hebrew of<lb/> the 25<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Ultim. kindly send me<lb/> by my valued Friend Mrs Mendy<lb/> of New Port Rhode Island that<lb/> I might read in extenso the<lb/> high and deserved honor<lb/> confered<sic></sic> on you by the<lb/> University of Pennsylvania<lb/> I could not refrain in<lb/> sending you&#44; in the names<lb/> of your old English pupils<lb/> and self our united warm<lb/> congratulation on the dis&#45;<lb/>tinction confered<sic></sic> on you<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the which we pray you<lb/> may enjoy for very many<lb/> years the health and peace<lb/> surrounded by your loving<lb/> children&#45;&#45;whose pride in<lb/> their good Father&#39;s account<lb/> I can not imagine&#45;&#45;We<lb/> feel not a little proud to say<lb/> <hi rend="underline">we</hi> also have known and<lb/> opp&#91;&#63;&#93;ated the Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> S. Morais<lb/> and parted with him with<lb/> regret a regret now turned<lb/> into pleasure&#44; in hearing of<lb/> his being more fully so&#44; by<lb/> abler heads none have ever<lb/> felt more kindly disposed<lb/> towards you than did my<lb/> loved and lamented Husband&#45;&#45;<lb/> I note by the same paper&#44;<lb/> you are likely to mix the<lb/> Minhag of the <hi rend="underline">two</hi> congregations<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>I think I remember the<lb/> time when you would have<lb/> resented the &#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; pleased<lb/> to note they write you a<lb/> conservative&#45;&#45;<hi rend="underline">Our</hi> cause<lb/> is therefore safe in your able<lb/> hands&#45;&#45;we have made the<lb/> move in having a German as<lb/> our Hakane&#45;&#45;not a Dr Artou&#45;<lb/>tent a long pleasing &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> and repeated &#91;&#63;&#93; the congre&#45;<lb/>gation have taken very kindly<lb/> to him.  Have neither of your<lb/> sons any curiosity to visit the<lb/> mother country or have they<lb/> some objection to a monarchal<lb/> Government as you now &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> &#91;&#63;&#93; of one thing I beg you<lb/> will address them that none<lb/> would be more pleased to<lb/> make the acquaintance of their<lb/> Father&#39;s children than my&#45;<lb/>&#61;self&#45;&#45;my sister&#44; and &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>offer their kind remembrances<lb/> and good wishes for<lb/> years of happy enjoyment<lb/> of your honors.  And<lb/> with assurance of regard<lb/> remain<lb/> yrs truly<lb/> Sarah Almosinia&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/>  Please note the address<lb/> The Revd S. Morais<lb/></p>
            </body>
